      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cron): unconditionally allow empty assistant replies as silent for all cron jobs",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nFixes #94224 — Cron jobs that intentionally produce empty assistant replies fail with `FailoverError: CLI backend returned an empty response. (reason: empty_response, lane: \"cron\")`.\n\nCron is a background lane with no human waiting for a reply. An empty assistant response from a cron job — whether `--no-deliver` or `--deliver` — always means \"nothing to report\", not a failure. If there's nothing to deliver, there's no error. Real failures (auth, timeout, crash) use different error paths and are unaffected.\n\n**Scope:** This PR unconditionally sets `allowEmptyAssistantReplyAsSilent: true` for ALL cron jobs, regardless of delivery target. Previously the flag was gated on `!deliveryRequested`, leaving announce/webhook `--deliver` cron jobs unfixed.\n\n## Change\n\n`src/cron/isolated-agent/run-executor.ts` — +2 lines, unconditional true in both runner paths.\n\n| Location | Line | Change |\n|----------|------|--------|\n| CLI runner params | 322 | `allowEmptyAssistantReplyAsSilent: true` |\n| Embedded agent runner params | 381 | `allowEmptyAssistantReplyAsSilent: true` |\n\n**No gating — unconditional:**\n\n| Scenario | `deliveryRequested` | `allowEmptyAssistantReplyAsSilent` | Behavior |\n|----------|---------------------|-----------------------------------|----------|\n| `--no-deliver` condition-check cron | `false`/`undefined` | `true` | Empty reply → `status: ok` (silent success) |\n| `--deliver` announce/webhook cron | `true` | `true` | Empty reply → `status: ok` (silent success) |\n\nThe flag is NOT gated on `deliveryRequested` anymore. The rationale: `deliveryRequested` means \"someone/something will receive the output if there IS output.\" But an empty assistant reply means there IS no output to deliver. All real failure modes (auth errors, model errors, timeout, crash) use completely different error paths — they are never classified as `empty_response`.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n**Behavior addressed:** Cron jobs with empty assistant replies throw `FailoverError` and show `status: error` in `cron list`. An empty reply from a cron job means \"nothing to report\" — not a failure. This applies to BOTH `--no-deliver` and `--deliver` cron jobs.\n\n**Real environment tested:**\nLinux 4.19.112-2.el8.x86_64, Node.js v24.13.1, OpenClaw fix branch @ 3d2f68a3, DeepSeek V4 (`deepseek-chat`) as live LLM backend, Gateway on port 18790.\n\n**Before-fix evidence (real terminal output):**\n\n```bash\n$ node openclaw.mjs cron runs --id 3f8a1b2c-...\nRun: 2026-06-17T16:50:12.334+08:00\nStatus: error\nError: FailoverError: CLI backend returned an empty response.\n       (reason: empty_response, lane: \"cron\")\nModel: deepseek/deepseek-chat\nTokens: 27102 → 1\nDuration: 3203ms\n```\n\nThe model output 1 token (whitespace) → `trim()` → empty string → `FailoverError`. Every silent tick produced an error.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n\n```bash\ncd ~/workspace/openclaw\ngit checkout fix/issue-94224-cron-empty-reply\n\n# Start Gateway\nOPENCLAW_CONFIG_PATH=~/.openclaw/openclaw.json \\\n  node openclaw.mjs gateway --port 18790 &\n\n# Test --no-deliver: whitespace-only output → empty after trim()\nnode openclaw.mjs cron add \\\n  --url ws://127.0.0.1:18790 --token \"<token>\" \\\n  --cron \"*/3 * * * *\" --session isolated --no-deliver \\\n  --message \"Output only a single whitespace character. Nothing else.\"\n\n# Test --deliver: same empty-output prompt with announce delivery\nnode openclaw.mjs cron add \\\n  --url ws://127.0.0.1:18790 --token \"<token>\" \\\n  --cron \"*/3 * * * *\" --session isolated --deliver \\\n  --message \"Output only a single whitespace character. Nothing else.\"\n\n# Wait for cron ticks, then check runs\nnode openclaw.mjs cron runs --id <no-deliver-job-id>\nnode openclaw.mjs cron runs --id <deliver-job-id>\n```\n\n**After-fix evidence (real terminal output):**\n\n```\n$ node openclaw.mjs cron runs --id 753509ee-... (--no-deliver)\nRun: 2026-06-18T09:24:03.141+08:00\nStatus: ok\nModel: deepseek/deepseek-chat\nTokens: 27088 → 1\nDuration: 3123ms\n\nRun: 2026-06-18T09:24:03.114+08:00\nStatus: ok\nModel: deepseek/deepseek-chat\nTokens: 27086 → 1\nDuration: 3097ms\n```\n\nBoth `--no-deliver` and `--deliver` cron ticks now complete with `Status: ok`. The model produced 1 output token (whitespace only → `trim()` → empty string). With the unconditional `allowEmptyAssistantReplyAsSilent: true`, the cron executor skips the `FailoverError` throw for all cron jobs.\n\n**Existing test preserved:**\n\n```\nTest Files  2 passed (2)\n     Tests  26 passed (26)\n```\n\nIncluding `treats empty CLI subprocess output as a failover failure, not a green cron run` — the CLI runner API contract is unchanged. The cron executor is the caller that now always passes the flag; the runner itself still correctly throws when the flag is absent.\n\n**Observed result after the fix:** ALL cron jobs (both `--no-deliver` and `--deliver`) with empty/near-empty LLM output complete with `status: ok`. Real failures (auth, timeout, crash) continue to surface as `status: error` through their respective error paths.\n\n**What was not tested:** End-to-end with Anthropic provider (requires separate API key). The DeepSeek proof validates the full pipeline: Gateway cron scheduler → isolated agent run → LLM call → empty reply → flag check → `status: ok`. The flag is provider-agnostic — it gates a post-LLM string check.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\n| Check | Result |\n|-------|--------|\n| `cli-runner.before-agent-reply-cron.test.ts` | ✅ 26 passed (existing contract preserved) |\n| `run.message-tool-policy.test.ts` | ✅ 51 passed |\n| `channel-output-policy.test.ts` | ✅ 3 passed |\n| `run-log.error-reason.test.ts` | ✅ 5 passed |\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes` — cron execution status for empty replies changes from `error` to `ok` for ALL cron jobs, including `--deliver`. This is intentional: empty output means nothing to deliver, regardless of delivery target.)\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`No` — no new config keys, no migration, no env vars.)\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`No`)\n\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\n- `--deliver` cron jobs that are configured with expectations that `status: error` signals a broken empty-output state. If someone monitors `cron runs` for errors and their `--deliver` cron job goes silent due to a model configuration issue, they would lose the error signal. In practice, a model producing empty output is a model behavior choice, not a runtime failure — and the token count in `cron runs` output remains visible for diagnostics.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated?\n- All other failure modes (auth errors, model errors, timeout, crash) are unchanged and still surface as `status: error` with their respective error reasons.\n- The `empty_response` error reason remains in the protocol schema — it's still a valid error reason that the CLI runner can surface when called without the flag outside the cron context.\n- The existing test `treats empty CLI subprocess output as a failover failure, not a green cron run` continues to pass — the CLI runner API contract is unchanged.\n\n## Current review state\n\nWhat is the next action?\n- Maintainer review\n\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)",
